'''[[Discrimination]] towards [[gender variant]] persons who fall outside of the [[gender binary]]''' is [[prejudice]] towards individuals who do not fit the [[gender binary]] as strictly [[male]] or [[female]]. It is a type of [[transphobia]]<ref>{{cite journal|last=Norton|first=Jody|title="Brain Says You're a Girl, But I Think You're a Sissy Boy": Cultural Origins of Transphobia|journal=International Journal of Sexuality and Gender Studies|year=1997|volume=2, Number 2|pages=139–164|doi=10.1023/A:1026320611878|issue=2}}</ref> and sexism.<ref name="Levesque2011">{{cite book | author = Roger J.R. Levesque | title = Encyclopedia of Adolescence | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=VdPGF1tfDJsC&pg=PA2641 | accessdate = 20 September 2012 | date = 5 September 2011 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4419-1694-5 | page = 2641}}</ref><ref name="LeongPickren2011">{{cite book | author1 = Frederick T.L. Leong | author2 = Wade E. Pickren | author3 = Mark M. Leach | coauthors = Anthony J. Marsella | title = Internationalizing the Psychology Curriculum in the United States | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=RrATt7OYuP0C&pg=PA163 | accessdate = 20 September 2012 | date = 1 November 2011 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4614-0072-1 | page = 163}}</ref> It primarily affects [[genderqueer]] people but can also affect other non-binary individuals such as [[third gender]] individuals. [[Cisgender]] and binary [[transgender]] people can also display prejudice against non-binary people, and there is discrimination of this sort in the transgender community much like there is transphobia in the [[lesbian]], [[gay]], [[bisexual]], and transgender ([[LGBT]]) communities.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Preves|first=Sharon Elaine|title=Negotiating the Constraints of Gender Binarism: Intersexuals' Challenge to Gender Categorization|journal=Current Sociology|year=2000|month=July|volume=48|issue=3|pages=27–50|doi=10.1177/0011392100048003004}}</ref> 

A study in the ''National Transgender Discrimination Survey'' showed that genderqueer and other non-binary individuals were more likely to be unemployed (76% vs. 56%), suffer physical assaults (32% vs. 25%), experience police brutality and harassment (31% vs. 21%), and opt out of medical treatment due to discrimination (36% vs. 27%) compared to transgender individuals who identified within the gender binary (i.e., [[trans man|trans men]] and [[trans woman|trans women]]). This study also found that they were more likely to be [[people of color]] (30% vs. 23%) and younger (under 45) than binary transgender people (89% vs. 68%).<ref name="Harrison2011">{{cite journal | author = Jack Harrison, Jaime Grant, Jody L. Herman | title = A Gender Not Listed Here: Genderqueers, Gender Rebels, and Otherwise in the National Transgender Discrimination Survey | publisher = Harvard Kennedy School | journal = LGBTQ Policy Journal | volume = 2 | issue = | page = 22 | year = 2011–2012 | month = | doi = | url = http://www.thetaskforce.org/downloads/release_materials/agendernotlistedhere.pdf | format = PDF}}</ref>

